{{for|the video game|Airball (video game)}}
{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2011}}

In basketball, an '''air ball''' is an unblocked shot which misses the basket, the rim, and the backboard entirely.{{refn|Definitions:<br />
*SportingCharts: Unblocked, doesn't touch the rim or the backboard.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportingcharts.com/dictionary/nba/air-ball.aspx|title=Air Ball|publisher=sportingcharts.com}}</ref>
*Merriam Webster: Completely misses the basket, rim, and backboard.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/air%20ball|title=Definition of air ball|publisher=merriam-webster.com}}</ref>
*Oxford: Misses the basket and backboard entirely.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.oxforddictionaries.com/definition/air_ball|title=air ball|publisher=oxforddictionaries.com}}</ref>
*dictionary.com: Missed shot that fails to touch the rim, net, or backboard.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dictionary.com/browse/air-ball|title=air ball|publisher=dictionary.com}}</ref>}}

==Origin==
The [[Oxford English Dictionary]] cites earliest printed use of "air ball" in a 29 January 1967 article from the (Hayward, Calif.) [[Daily Review]], which reads: "Cal State, four times lofting air balls at an orange basket that may as well have been painted invisible."<ref>{{cite web|title=air, n. 1|url=http://www.oed.com/view/Entry/4366?redirectedFrom=airball|work=OED Online|publisher=Oxford UP|accessdate=1 December 2012}}{{subscription required|date=August 2017}}</ref>  

An air ball by an opposing player during a competitive game will usually prompt fans (primarily in the [[college basketball|college game]]) present to [[chant]] “Aiiiir ball! Aiir ball!” repeatedly in a continuous drone to [[humiliation|humiliate]] the shooter. Since the 1980s, it has become common to restart the chant the next time the shooter touches the ball.

