{{refimprove|date=July 2007}}
A '''Snickometer''', commonly known as '''Snicko''', is used in televising [[cricket]] to graphically analyse sound and video, and show whether a fine noise, or snick, occurs as ball passes bat. It was invented by English computer scientist Allan Plaskett<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/first-the-snickometer-now-for-the-lbw-detector-718925.html |title=First the snickometer, now for the lbw detector |last=Fay |first=Steven |date=21 May 2000 |publisher=The Independent |accessdate=17 June 2010}}</ref> in the mid-1990s. The snickometer was introduced by [[Channel 4]] in the UK, who also introduced the [[Hawk-Eye]] and the Red Zone,<ref>{{Cite book | year=2006 | title=Broadcasting Rights for Cricket: Ashes to Ashes - the Death Knell for Live Test Match Cricket on Free-to-air TV?; First Report of Session 2005-06; Report, Together with Formal Minutes, Oral and Written Evidence | author1=Media and Sport Committee Culture, Parliament, House of Commons | publisher=The Stationery Office | isbn=978-0-215-02723-8 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-kbnL62Aj28C&pg=RA1-PA23&dq=snickometer | postscript=<!--None-->}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book | year=2008 | title=Pommies | author1=William Buckland | publisher=Troubador Publishing Ltd | isbn=978-1-906510-32-9 | page=162 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1Aqvrj1YuggC&pg=PA162&dq=snickometer | postscript=<!--None-->}}</ref> in 1999.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/cricket-channel-4-reveals-the-sensational-snickometer-1102323.html | work=The Independent | location=London | title=Cricket: Channel 4 reveals the sensational Snickometer | first=Chris | last=Maume | date=1999-06-25 | accessdate=2010-05-23}}</ref>
== Uses == {{mainarticle|Umpire Decision Review System}}
The Snickometer is often used in a [[slow motion]] [[television]] [[Instant replay|replay]] by the third umpire to determine if the [[cricket ball]] touched the [[cricket bat]] on the way through to the [[wicketkeeper]]. The commentators will listen and view the shape of the recorded soundwave. If there is a sound of leather on willow, which is usually a short sharp sound in synchrony with the ball passing the bat, then the ball has touched the bat. Other sounds such as the ball hitting the batsman's pads, or the bat hitting the pitch biscuit , and so on, tend to have a fatter shape on the sound [[waveform]].
If, in the [[Umpire (cricket)|umpire's]] opinion, this is the case, and the ball was a legal delivery that was caught before touching the ground, then the batsman is given out by the umpire. The umpire does not have the benefit of the Snickometer, and must instead rely on his senses of sight and hearing, as well as his judgement. When the Umpire [[Umpire Decision Review System|DRS]] (Decision Review System) was introduced to Test Cricket, Snicko was not considered accurate enough, and so another edge detecting tool [[Hot Spot (cricket)|Hot Spot]] was used.
Channel 4 in the UK and Channel Nine of Australia, amongst others, have used it to help determine if the batsman was out or not. In 2013, Allan Plaskett was operating it for Sky TV.
