{{Infobox swimmer | name = Tracy Ann Route | image = <!-- Only free-content images are allowed for depicting living people -- see [[WP:NONFREE]]. --> | image_size = <!-- Only for images narrower than 220 pixels --> | caption = | fullname = Tracy Ann Route | nicknames = | national_team = {{flag|FSM|name=Micronesia}} | strokes = [[Freestyle swimming|Freestyle]], [[Butterfly swimming|butterfly]] | club = | coach = | collegeteam = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1985|2|23|df=yes}} | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | height = {{convert|1.57|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}} | weight = {{convert|43|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}} | medaltemplates = | show-medals = yes | updated = }}
'''Tracy Ann Route''' (born February 23, 1985) is a Micronesian former swimmer, who specialized in sprint freestyle and butterfly events.<ref>{{cite sports-reference|Tracy Ann Route|https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ro/tracy-ann-route-1.html|7 May 2013}}</ref> She is a two-time Olympian (2000 and 2004), and holds numerous Pacific age group records in the freestyle and butterfly (both 50 and 100 m).
When Micronesia marked its Olympic debut at the [[2000 Summer Olympics]] in [[Sydney]], Route competed as a 15-year-old in the [[Swimming at the 2000 Summer Olympics – Women's 100 metre butterfly|women's 100 m butterfly]]. Swimming in heat one, she rounded out a field to last place and forty-ninth overall against Swaziland's [[Lisa de la Motte]] and Malta's [[Angela Galea]] with a slowest time of 1:13.53.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sydney 2000: Swimming – Women's 100m Butterfly Heat 1 |url=http://www.la84foundation.org/6oic/OfficialReports/2000/Masters/sw/SWresults.pdf |format=[[PDF]] |work=[[Sydney 2000]] |publisher=[[LA84 Foundation]] |page=224 |accessdate=19 April 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110819181023/http://la84foundation.org/6oic/OfficialReports/2000/Masters/sw/SWresults.pdf |archivedate=19 August 2011 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Newberry|first=Paul|title=Thompson anchors U.S. relay win; Thorpe wins 400 free|url=http://www.canoe.ca/2000GamesSwimming/sep16_tho.html|publisher=[[Canoe.ca]]|date=16 September 2000|accessdate=28 May 2013}}</ref>
At the [[2004 Summer Olympics]] in [[Athens]], Route decided to swim only for the [[Swimming at the 2004 Summer Olympics – Women's 50 metre freestyle|50 m freestyle]]. She received a Universality place from [[FINA]] in an entry time of 32.44.<ref>{{cite web|title=Swimming – Women's 50m Freestyle Startlist (Heat 2)|url=http://www.omegatiming.com/File/Download?id=000104060049000000FFFFFFFFFFFF00|format=[[PDF]]|work=[[Athens 2004]]|publisher=Omega Timing|accessdate=19 April 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Minginifel qualifies for Athens Olympics|url=http://www.fsmgov.org/press/pr07080b.htm|publisher=FSM National Government|date=20 August 2004|accessdate=7 May 2013}}</ref> She challenged six other swimmers in heat two, including 14-year-olds [[Sameera Al-Bitar]] of Bahrain and [[Christal Clashing]] of Antigua and Barbuda. She posted a lifetime best of 31.26 to earn a third spot by 0.26 of a second behind joint winners Al-Bitar and [[Ghazal El Jobeili]] of Lebanon. Route failed to advance into the semifinals, as she shared a sixty-fifth place tie with Maldives' [[Aminath Rouya Hussain]] on the last day of prelims.<ref>{{cite web|title=Women's 50m Freestyle Heat 2|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/olympics_2004/swimming/results/3535060.stm|work=[[Athens 2004]]|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=20 August 2004|accessdate=31 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Thomas |first=Stephen |title=Women's 50 Freestyle, Prelims Day 7: Inky Sizzles in World Best 24.66, Joyce Next in PR 25.06, Jenny Thompson Makes It Too |url=http://www.swimmingworldmagazine.com/lane9/news/7915.asp |publisher=[[Swimming World Magazine]] |date=20 August 2004 |accessdate=19 April 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120204111631/http://www.swimmingworldmagazine.com/lane9/news/7915.asp |archivedate= 4 February 2012 |df= }}</ref>
